      "name": "How long does it take to build a retaining wall in Pakenham?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "A typical residential wall of 10&ndash;15 lineal metres at 900mm height takes 2&ndash;3 trade days on site once the permit and engineering are in hand. Engineered walls over 1m that require a building permit add 2&ndash;6 weeks for the engineering and permit process before construction starts. Full timeline: site assessment 1&ndash;2 days, engineering and permit 2&ndash;6 weeks, construction 2&ndash;3 days."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Why is drainage so important in a Pakenham retaining wall build?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Cardinia Shire sits on reactive M&ndash;H clay that holds and absorbs water heavily in winter. Without a sub-soil ag-drain, free-draining aggregate backfill, and functioning weep holes, hydrostatic pressure builds behind the wall every wet season. That pressure is the number-one cause of retaining wall bulging and failure in Pakenham &mdash; usually visible within 5&ndash;8 years of a wall built without proper drainage."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "How deep do post footings need to be for a retaining wall in Pakenham?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "As a rule of thumb, post embed depth should be roughly equal to the retained height for timber sleeper walls on reactive clay &mdash; so a 900mm-high wall needs posts embedded about 900mm. For concrete sleeper walls the engineer typically specifies 600&ndash;1,000mm of embedment depending on post spacing and retained height. These depths are deeper than the Bayside or Mornington Peninsula defaults because Cardinia clay is reactive and heavier-loaded."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What is the difference between compacted backfill and normal backfill in a retaining wall?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Free-draining aggregate (20mm scoria or crushed rock) is placed immediately behind the wall to allow water to move to the ag-drain. Behind that, engineered fill or suitable site material is placed and compacted in 150&ndash;200mm layers. Uncompacted backfill settles unevenly, loads the wall unpredictably, and can leave voids that collapse. Proper compaction in layers is what keeps the finished surface stable above the wall."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Does excavation on Pakenham clay cause extra complications?",
